<author><name><![CDATA[tepples]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-04-05T15:16:32-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-04-05T15:16:32-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6258&amp;p=59684#p59684</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6258&amp;p=59684#p59684"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[ASM6 Tuts]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6258&amp;p=59684#p59684"><![CDATA[
I'm with Banshaku. <a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/make/" class="postlink">GNU Make</a> has a few advantages over a batch file, especially if you use an assembler with an "object file" mentality like ca65:<br /><ul><li>With a makefile, only those things that need to get rebuilt get rebuilt. You specify what files depends on what other files, and Make does a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Topological_sorting" class="postlink">topological sort</a> on them and then builds a plan based on file modification dates. </li><li><a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/make.html#Parallel" class="postlink">make -j2</a> so that one process can compile while the other blocks on disk I/O. </li><li>make -j3 so that both cores of a dual-core CPU can compile while a third process blocks on disk I/O. </li><li><a href="http://www.gnu.org/software/make/manual/make.html#Pattern-Rules" class="postlink">Pattern rules</a>. For example, if the commands to assemble most of your .s files are the same except for filenames, you can capture this similarity. </li><li>Specify multiple targets. For example, a single makefile can handle making the data conversion tools, making the executable, making the unit test executable, making the documentation, and making the zipfile, and arguments to 'make' tell which targets shall be built. </li><li>It automatically halts on syntax errors without having to 'if errorlevel 1 goto End' all the time. </li></ul><br />If you have MSYS, you have GNU Make. If you have devkitARM or devkitPPC from other Nintendo console homebrew scenes, you have devkitPro MSYS.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=9">tepples</a> — Mon Apr 05, 2010 3:16 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
